00:22:54.520 --> 00:22:57.780
The lyrics that they
used in the songs

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:00.170
gave me the answers
to the problems that I

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:01.520
thought I had at the time.

00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:03.670
I was lonely.

00:23:03.670 --> 00:23:07.160
I was this disenfranchised
kid who really wanted

00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:09.188
to do something that mattered.

00:23:09.188 --> 00:23:12.646
I wanted to belong to something
because I was pretty lonely.

00:23:12.646 --> 00:23:14.640
And music was the
tool that brought me

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:17.010
in to this subculture.

00:23:17.010 --> 00:23:21.430
And in fact, it's probably the
most powerful propaganda tool

00:23:21.430 --> 00:23:25.610
that racists in our
country, and even abroad,

00:23:25.610 --> 00:23:29.322
have to recruit young people.

00:23:29.322 --> 00:23:32.660
So it's a pretty powerful
tool that's used.

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:35.860
As far as Joan
Jett goes, in '96,

00:23:35.860 --> 00:23:37.371
after I'd left
the movement, when

00:23:37.371 --> 00:23:38.870
I was going through
that depression,

00:23:38.870 --> 00:23:42.400
I started a punk band because
it was really the only thing

00:23:42.400 --> 00:23:43.337
that I knew how to do.

00:23:43.337 --> 00:23:43.920
I loved music.

00:23:43.920 --> 00:23:45.534
I knew how to play
music, and I wanted

00:23:45.534 --> 00:23:47.700
to do something that was
completely opposite of what

00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:50.210
I had spent seven years doing.

00:23:50.210 --> 00:23:53.000
And one of our first shows
happened by accident.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:56.840
We were asked to open
a show for Joan Jett.

00:23:56.840 --> 00:23:58.860
And of course, we said yes.

00:23:58.860 --> 00:24:02.080
And during our soundcheck,
after our soundcheck,

00:24:02.080 --> 00:24:05.170
Joan had noticed me backstage,
and I was depressed.

00:24:05.170 --> 00:24:06.250
I was probably drunk.

00:24:06.250 --> 00:24:09.493
And she came up to me
and put her arm around me

00:24:09.493 --> 00:24:11.240
and said, hey.

00:24:11.240 --> 00:24:12.238
Are you OK?

00:24:12.238 --> 00:24:13.193
And I didnt know her.

00:24:13.193 --> 00:24:14.234
I'd never met her before.

00:24:14.234 --> 00:24:17.230
I was slightly starstruck by it.

00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:18.930
And I started to
tell her my story.

00:24:18.930 --> 00:24:21.138
I didn't mention that I was
involved in the movement,

00:24:21.138 --> 00:24:24.839
but I had mentioned that I was
going through some tough times.

00:24:24.839 --> 00:24:26.630
And she put her arm
around me, and she said

00:24:26.630 --> 00:24:27.830
you guys were really great.

00:24:27.830 --> 00:24:29.371
You guys should come
on tour with us.

00:24:29.371 --> 00:24:31.189
And she didn't have to do that.

00:24:31.189 --> 00:24:31.980
She didn't know me.

00:24:31.980 --> 00:24:33.604
She didn't know
anything about my band.

00:24:33.604 --> 00:24:37.370
She didn't know if we were
gonna sell tickets that night.

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:39.770
And it was one of
the first moments

00:24:39.770 --> 00:24:41.898
after this depression
of not talking

00:24:41.898 --> 00:24:43.750
about what I'd been
through that allowed

00:24:43.750 --> 00:24:46.668
me to realize that there
were people out there that

00:24:46.668 --> 00:24:49.110
cared about me.

00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:52.510
So years later, we'd
done some touring.

00:24:52.510 --> 00:24:54.610
She had managed us
for a little while.

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:57.304
Years later, when I
decided to finish the book,

00:24:57.304 --> 00:24:59.256
I approached Joan and
I told her the story.

00:24:59.256 --> 00:25:00.714
And I told her my
whole background.

00:25:00.714 --> 00:25:02.105
And she was shocked.

00:25:02.105 --> 00:25:02.674
She didn't know
anything about it,

00:25:02.674 --> 00:25:04.215
but she agreed to
write the foreword,

00:25:04.215 --> 00:25:06.342
and I think it's a
beautiful foreword.

00:25:06.342 --> 00:25:09.276
I'm really glad that she did it.

00:25:09.276 --> 00:25:12.210
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: So you
talk about the movement.

00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:15.633
You say the movement--
most people don't really

00:25:15.633 --> 00:25:18.567
know much about the skinhead
culture and the movement.

00:25:18.567 --> 00:25:21.501
I've learned a ton
from you, obviously,

00:25:21.501 --> 00:25:23.960
just going through
this process with you.

00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:27.950
But we don't hear a lot
about these domestic groups.

00:25:27.950 --> 00:25:29.460
We hear a lot about ISIS.

00:25:29.460 --> 00:25:30.520
We hear about ISIL.

00:25:30.520 --> 00:25:33.377
We hear a lot about
what I would consider

00:25:33.377 --> 00:25:35.373
international
non-domestic things.

00:25:35.373 --> 00:25:37.831
We don't hear a lot about that,
and I think a lot of people

00:25:37.831 --> 00:25:39.590
are surprised to hear
some of the facts

00:25:39.590 --> 00:25:42.840
about some of the current
organizations in the United

00:25:42.840 --> 00:25:43.340
States.

00:25:43.340 --> 00:25:46.280
If you could talk a
little about that.

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:50.320
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: In
the mid-80s til the mid-90s,

00:25:50.320 --> 00:25:52.903
you could walk down
the streets of Chicago

00:25:52.903 --> 00:25:55.410
and chances are pretty good you
would come across a skinhead

00:25:55.410 --> 00:25:58.560
or somebody that looked like
a skinhead-- shaved head,

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:01.730
tattoos, boots.

00:26:01.730 --> 00:26:04.315
Nowadays, you don't
see that as much.

00:26:04.315 --> 00:26:05.690
Because one of
the things that we

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:08.300
taught when I was part
of the organization

00:26:08.300 --> 00:26:10.050
was a concept called
leaderless resistance

00:26:10.050 --> 00:26:14.630
and mainstreaming, which
taught people who were attached

00:26:14.630 --> 00:26:17.310
to these groups to blend in,

00:26:17.310 --> 00:26:19.880
So while you may
not see skinheads

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:23.575
throwing chairs on the
Geraldo Show or the Oprah Show

00:26:23.575 --> 00:26:27.010
or whatever anymore,
they absolutely exist.

00:26:27.010 --> 00:26:29.390
As a matter of fact,
the FBI just this year

00:26:29.390 --> 00:26:33.160
released a report that
listed their top perceived

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:35.450
homegrown terrorist threats.

00:26:35.450 --> 00:26:40.970
And of the 12 that were listed,
ISIS was not number one.

00:26:40.970 --> 00:26:43.220
You would think because we
talk about it all the time.

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:44.095
They were number two.

00:26:44.095 --> 00:26:47.920
Number one was a
group of white racists

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:49.660
called Sovereign Citizens.

00:26:49.660 --> 00:26:52.760
Number three was
neo-Nazi skinheads.

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:54.500
Number four was Ku Klux Klan.

00:26:54.500 --> 00:26:56.412
Number five was
Christian Identity.

00:26:56.412 --> 00:26:59.310
What I'm trying to say is
all these groups put together

00:26:59.310 --> 00:27:03.520
are what I was, just segmented.

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:05.440
So while we hear
a lot in the media

00:27:05.440 --> 00:27:12.330
about middle class girls
going to Syria to join ISIS,

00:27:12.330 --> 00:27:16.665
and that happens, I would
caution that there is probably

00:27:16.665 --> 00:27:21.980
a bigger threat in this country
from far right extremists.

00:27:21.980 --> 00:27:26.720
Though you may not see them,
I assure you they're there.

00:27:26.720 --> 00:27:30.940
We see these things when a lone
wolf like Wade Michael Page

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:34.690
walks into a Sikh temple in Oak
Creek, Wisconsin and murderers,

00:27:34.690 --> 00:27:37.005
tragically, seven
innocent people.

00:27:37.005 --> 00:27:40.910
We hear it when
Randal Lee Krager

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:45.133
goes to a synagogue
parking lot in Missouri

00:27:45.133 --> 00:27:49.206
and shoots who he thinks
are four Jewish people.

00:27:49.206 --> 00:27:50.572
It happens all the time.

00:27:50.572 --> 00:27:52.030
It doesn't happen
on a large scale.

00:27:52.030 --> 00:27:54.315
It happens on an
individualized scale

00:27:54.315 --> 00:27:59.819
and on a lone wolf basis, which
I think is much more dangerous.

00:27:59.819 --> 00:28:01.735
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: Why
doesn't the media seem

00:28:01.735 --> 00:28:05.724
to put that angle out there?

00:28:05.724 --> 00:28:07.197
I was shocked to
hear through you

00:28:07.197 --> 00:28:10.640
that the Oklahoma
bombings were actually

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:12.347
related to the movement.

00:28:12.347 --> 00:28:13.472
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: Yeah.

00:28:13.472 --> 00:28:14.930
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
It doesn't seem

00:28:14.930 --> 00:28:16.700
like that was a
story at the time,

00:28:16.700 --> 00:28:19.765
that that was a piece
of it, that it was just

00:28:19.765 --> 00:28:21.290
a lone wolf and a
horrific bombing.

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:22.110
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Yeah, Timothy McVeigh

00:28:22.110 --> 00:28:24.780
was found with a book called
"The Turner Diaries," which

00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:28.340
was a book written-- a
fictional book that was written

00:28:28.340 --> 00:28:32.880
about white extremists
blowing up a federal building

00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:36.963
and causing widespread
chaos and murder.

00:28:36.963 --> 00:28:40.545
And Timothy McVeigh was found
with copies of the book.

00:28:40.545 --> 00:28:43.870
There was a copy of
the book in the van.

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:46.360
Why you don't hear about them?

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:48.685
I'm not really sure.

00:28:48.685 --> 00:28:51.350
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: Is
it lack of knowledge?

00:28:51.350 --> 00:28:51.863
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
No, I don't

00:28:51.863 --> 00:28:53.071
think it's lack of knowledge.

00:28:53.071 --> 00:28:54.690
I mean, media tends
to go with stories

00:28:54.690 --> 00:28:58.465
that are a little bit more
exciting, and not exciting

00:28:58.465 --> 00:29:00.540
in a positive way.

00:29:00.540 --> 00:29:06.390
But the media focuses on
what's hot at the moment.

00:29:06.390 --> 00:29:09.530
But lone wolf activities
happen all the time.

00:29:09.530 --> 00:29:11.594
Every year, there's
dozens and dozens

00:29:11.594 --> 00:29:15.260
of these tragedies that happen.

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:20.216
They don't point the finger
at them and I don't know why.

00:29:20.216 --> 00:29:22.591
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: You've
done quite a bit of consulting

00:29:22.591 --> 00:29:26.487
with different law
enforcement organizations,

00:29:26.487 --> 00:29:28.440
with the Anti-Defamation League.

00:29:28.440 --> 00:29:34.110
Talk about what they look for
from you, from your experience.

00:29:34.110 --> 00:29:36.700
What kind of things are they
trying to understand and gain

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:37.637
from you?

00:29:37.637 --> 00:29:39.720
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: So
like the video mentioned,

00:29:39.720 --> 00:29:41.910
in 2010, I co-founded
an organization called

00:29:41.910 --> 00:29:48.980
Life After Hate, which was set
up specifically to-- initially

00:29:48.980 --> 00:29:52.380
it was set up for my partner
and I, when we found ourselves

00:29:52.380 --> 00:29:55.610
after years of not knowing
what each other was doing,

00:29:55.610 --> 00:29:58.147
he had left the movement
and had kids the same age.

00:29:58.147 --> 00:30:00.230
I had left the movement
and had kids the same age.

00:30:00.230 --> 00:30:02.354
There was nowhere for us
to talk about our stories.

00:30:02.354 --> 00:30:06.452
So we launched lifeafterhate.org
as a literary magazine,

00:30:06.452 --> 00:30:09.600
an online magazine just
to talk about our stories.

00:30:09.600 --> 00:30:11.680
Very quickly, we were
overwhelmed with people

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:14.310
reaching out from all over the
world who had similar stories.

00:30:14.310 --> 00:30:18.100
Up until that time, there had
been no organization support

00:30:18.100 --> 00:30:19.972
group for people
who left hate groups

00:30:19.972 --> 00:30:24.440
or who wanted to leave
hate groups to get help.

00:30:24.440 --> 00:30:27.630
And we quickly found out
that, through Life After Hate,

00:30:27.630 --> 00:30:29.550
our unique perspective
was something

00:30:29.550 --> 00:30:32.466
that law enforcement, and
academia, and community

00:30:32.466 --> 00:30:33.440
organizations lacked.

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:34.610
They understood the problem.

00:30:34.610 --> 00:30:37.080
They understood that
there was a problem,

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:39.500
but not having spent
time in those groups,

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:43.850
they didn't really
have a solution

00:30:43.850 --> 00:30:46.080
to fix it from the inside out.

00:30:46.080 --> 00:30:49.730
So when Life After Hate
became more of a consulting

00:30:49.730 --> 00:30:52.340
organization, we started to
work with law enforcement

00:30:52.340 --> 00:30:55.280
and with higher education
to help them understand

00:30:55.280 --> 00:30:59.280
the mindset of how people are
recruited into these groups,

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:01.787
and likewise, what it
takes to deradicalize

00:31:01.787 --> 00:31:05.370
people who are coming out
of these organizations.

00:31:05.370 --> 00:31:10.680
Because, like myself, I
wasn't raised to be a racist.

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:11.930
It wasn't who I initially was.

00:31:11.930 --> 00:31:14.150
I went through a
seven year period

00:31:14.150 --> 00:31:16.625
where I was indoctrinated
and was passionate about what

00:31:16.625 --> 00:31:17.510
I believed in.

00:31:17.510 --> 00:31:20.070
But it wasn't my true self.

00:31:20.070 --> 00:31:23.190
So like me, there are thousands
of other people out there

00:31:23.190 --> 00:31:25.870
who went through that
and have never found out

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:28.620
how to integrate with
society in a positive way

00:31:28.620 --> 00:31:31.270
after they've left these groups,
whether it's because they're

00:31:31.270 --> 00:31:33.955
stigmatized or too scared to
talk about their experiences,

00:31:33.955 --> 00:31:35.871
or whether they've gone
to prison or whatever.

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:42.200
It was our goal to really
help them understand

00:31:42.200 --> 00:31:46.012
what it takes for people to
get introduced to these groups.

00:31:46.012 --> 00:31:47.970
It's a common problem,
and we see it with ISIS.

00:31:47.970 --> 00:31:49.630
We see it with other
extremist groups.

00:31:49.630 --> 00:31:50.504
We see it with gangs.

00:31:50.504 --> 00:31:53.330
There really isn't that much of
a difference between why people

00:31:53.330 --> 00:31:58.270
join an inner-city street gang
and why they become a neo-Nazi

00:31:58.270 --> 00:31:58.770
skinhead.

00:31:58.770 --> 00:31:59.769
It's look for attention.

00:31:59.769 --> 00:32:01.460
It's looking for
something to belong in.

00:32:01.460 --> 00:32:04.240
It's trying to find an
excuse for the problems

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:06.810
that you're experiencing
in your life.

00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:09.425
We never took responsibility
for our problems.

00:32:09.425 --> 00:32:11.334
It was always because
of somebody else.

00:32:11.334 --> 00:32:12.917
Black people would
move in, and that's

00:32:12.917 --> 00:32:14.254
why there was more crime.

00:32:14.254 --> 00:32:15.600
Or the Jews own the media.

00:32:15.600 --> 00:32:17.016
That's why they
talk bad about us.

00:32:17.016 --> 00:32:19.292
We never accepted the
responsibility ourselves

00:32:19.292 --> 00:32:21.276
that our lives were
pretty shitty because we

00:32:21.276 --> 00:32:23.260
made them pretty shitty.

00:32:23.260 --> 00:32:25.610
So we really want to
help organizations

00:32:25.610 --> 00:32:27.430
understand the mindset.

00:32:27.430 --> 00:32:30.069
Because we think that that
could help solve the problem.

00:32:30.069 --> 00:32:31.610
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
One of the things

00:32:31.610 --> 00:32:35.730
I was the most fascinated
by was to hear [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:35.730 --> 00:32:39.610
this magic age of 14,
13, 14, that, I think,

00:32:39.610 --> 00:32:42.120
a lot of you who came together
for a conference in Dublin

00:32:42.120 --> 00:32:45.490
against discovered when
you were all telling

00:32:45.490 --> 00:32:47.810
your story that there was a
common thread about a time

00:32:47.810 --> 00:32:50.210
in your life that you
actually became indoctrinated

00:32:50.210 --> 00:32:52.090
and part of the movement.

00:32:52.090 --> 00:32:53.090
Can you talk about that?

00:32:53.090 --> 00:32:53.860
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Yeah, that's

00:32:53.860 --> 00:32:55.300
actually an interesting story.

00:32:55.300 --> 00:32:59.530
And I ow a lot of the work that
Life After Hate does to Google.

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:04.010
Because in 2011,
Google Ideas sponsored

00:33:04.010 --> 00:33:07.660
in Dublin, Ireland, a summit
against violent extremism.

00:33:07.660 --> 00:33:10.260
It was the first
one of its kind,

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:13.940
and they invited about 150
former members of extremist

00:33:13.940 --> 00:33:17.080
groups-- and that was everything
from far right extremism,

00:33:17.080 --> 00:33:20.530
to former gang members,
to former IRA members,

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:25.140
to former Boko Haram, to you
name it-- but also invited

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:30.346
victims and survivors of
violence caused by extremists.

00:33:30.346 --> 00:33:32.220
And they put us all
in the same room.

00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:34.955
And it was Google Ideas and the
Council on Foreign Relations

00:33:34.955 --> 00:33:36.880
and the Tribeca
Film Festival who

00:33:36.880 --> 00:33:39.400
sponsored this event in Dublin.

00:33:39.400 --> 00:33:43.460
And what we realized after
talking to each other,

00:33:43.460 --> 00:33:46.930
this mind-bending experience
of being put in a room

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:49.560
and discussing what
we'd all been through,

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:51.680
that there's a pretty
common thread on why people

00:33:51.680 --> 00:33:52.590
join these groups.

00:33:52.590 --> 00:33:57.660
A lot of times it's young kids
around the ages of 12,13,14,

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:01.790
who are misguided and looking
for something to belong to,

00:34:01.790 --> 00:34:05.100
moreso looking to do
something that matters.

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:09.387
I could have been intercepted
by ballerinas or whoever.

00:34:09.387 --> 00:34:10.845
And I may have gone
down that path.

00:34:10.845 --> 00:34:13.940
It just happens that a
charismatic individual

00:34:13.940 --> 00:34:16.395
saw in me that I was
ambitious and looking

00:34:16.395 --> 00:34:17.552
for something to belong to.

00:34:17.552 --> 00:34:23.053
And it was a product of
environment and circumstance.

00:34:23.053 --> 00:34:25.060
But I mean there's a
really common thread

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:28.480
on why young people
join extremist groups.

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:31.400
It's no different from
why they join gangs.

00:34:31.400 --> 00:34:33.354
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
Which is what?

00:34:33.354 --> 00:34:35.770
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: I think
you're looking for something

00:34:35.770 --> 00:34:36.949
to belong to.

00:34:36.949 --> 00:34:41.870
For me, specifically, I
was a pretty ambitious kid.

00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:46.080
And when I saw this opportunity
to join a startup, which

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:49.462
is what the skinhead
movement was at the time,

00:34:49.462 --> 00:34:50.909
I jumped at the opportunity.

00:34:50.909 --> 00:34:53.936
There were these older guys who
were paying attention to me.

00:34:53.936 --> 00:34:56.810
I was given tasks that mattered.

00:34:56.810 --> 00:35:00.840
I would go to photocopy flyers,
and I would go put flyers

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:02.180
on their windshields.

00:35:02.180 --> 00:35:03.140
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
You were respected.

00:35:03.140 --> 00:35:03.690
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
I was respected

00:35:03.690 --> 00:35:06.100
and I was rewarded
for my hard work

00:35:06.100 --> 00:35:08.515
when everybody else
around me, like my family,

00:35:08.515 --> 00:35:12.910
was too busy to notice that
I needed that attention.

00:35:12.910 --> 00:35:15.334
So they paid attention to
me when I really needed it.

00:35:15.334 --> 00:35:17.750
And not to say that there was
any lack of love or anything

00:35:17.750 --> 00:35:18.850
in my life.

00:35:18.850 --> 00:35:21.780
Because I was always
surrounded by love.

00:35:21.780 --> 00:35:24.262
But I wasn't given
the attention that I

00:35:24.262 --> 00:35:28.050
was looking for, which was to
do something that mattered.

00:35:28.050 --> 00:35:29.425
So when they saw
that in me, they

00:35:29.425 --> 00:35:32.490
scooped me up pretty quickly.

00:35:32.490 --> 00:35:35.156
And it took me awhile to get
used to the politics of it.

00:35:35.156 --> 00:35:37.370
At first, it wasn't
about the politics.

00:35:37.370 --> 00:35:39.830
It was about the fashion and
being a part of this group.

00:35:39.830 --> 00:35:44.258
But I quickly
became indoctrinated

00:35:44.258 --> 00:35:47.186
into the politics, and I
was passionate about it.

00:35:47.186 --> 00:35:48.686
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
We're definitely

00:35:48.686 --> 00:35:50.670
going to have time
for a few questions.

00:35:50.670 --> 00:35:51.700
So think about what
you might want to ask.

00:35:51.700 --> 00:35:53.408
The last question I'll
have for Christian

00:35:53.408 --> 00:35:58.140
is a lot going on-- Baltimore,
pretty timely challenges

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:00.890
for the country right now.

00:36:00.890 --> 00:36:05.210
What are your thoughts on things
like Ferguson and Baltimore.

00:36:05.210 --> 00:36:07.870
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Well, I think it's tragic.

00:36:07.870 --> 00:36:11.751
I mean, we see it over and over
again in places like Ferguson,

00:36:11.751 --> 00:36:15.599
and New York, and Baltimore.

00:36:15.599 --> 00:36:18.485
And I think that change has
to come from the community.

00:36:18.485 --> 00:36:25.630
I think that community
leaders and faith leaders,

00:36:25.630 --> 00:36:29.135
the power's in their
hands to fix the situation

00:36:29.135 --> 00:36:31.050
in their communities.

00:36:31.050 --> 00:36:33.822
I also think that there's a
problem with law enforcement.

00:36:33.822 --> 00:36:38.080
I think that while
their job is to protect,

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:42.080
it is not so much
about serving anymore.

00:36:42.080 --> 00:36:44.990
Not to say that they
don't have a tough job,

00:36:44.990 --> 00:36:46.614
I think that law
enforcement is not

00:36:46.614 --> 00:36:47.726
doing a good enough job
to understand what's

00:36:47.726 --> 00:36:48.934
happening in the community.

00:36:48.934 --> 00:36:50.210
I think the community's
not doing enough

00:36:50.210 --> 00:36:52.970
to understand what's happening
at the law enforcement level.

00:36:52.970 --> 00:36:54.540
But i think what
it boils down to is

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:56.530
that there's a
lack of opportunity

00:36:56.530 --> 00:36:58.780
in a lot of these neighborhoods.

00:36:58.780 --> 00:37:06.136
And with desperation, sometimes,
comes civil disobedience.

00:37:06.136 --> 00:37:08.270
And for somebody who
doesn't have an option

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:14.330
to be heard, sometimes that
violence speaks the loudest.

00:37:14.330 --> 00:37:18.302
Not to say that it's right, and
I certainly don't support it,

00:37:18.302 --> 00:37:19.984
but I understand it.

00:37:19.984 --> 00:37:22.480
And I think we have
a lot of work to do.

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:24.970
For me, one thing that
changed me was empathy.

00:37:24.970 --> 00:37:29.229
I owned a record store in '95
when got out of the movement.

00:37:29.229 --> 00:37:31.187
I had started the record
store because I wanted

00:37:31.187 --> 00:37:32.558
to sell white power music.

00:37:32.558 --> 00:37:34.843
I was doing it out
of my backpack.

00:37:34.843 --> 00:37:38.074
And between getting laid
off from a construction job,

00:37:38.074 --> 00:37:40.800
I wanted to be an
entrepreneur, like my parents.

00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:43.571
So I went into the
business wanting

00:37:43.571 --> 00:37:45.071
to be fair to
everybody who came in.

00:37:45.071 --> 00:37:46.737
I wasn't just selling
white power music.

00:37:46.737 --> 00:37:48.990
I was selling ska, and
rockabilly, and punk.

00:37:48.990 --> 00:37:51.611
And I told myself I was
going to bite my tongue

00:37:51.611 --> 00:37:53.402
and serve everybody
fairly because I wanted

00:37:53.402 --> 00:37:56.301
to be a good businessman while
I was still selling white power

00:37:56.301 --> 00:37:59.490
music from behind the counter.

00:37:59.490 --> 00:38:01.600
One thing that
happened to me was

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:06.230
that people who I had
secluded myself from,

00:38:06.230 --> 00:38:10.390
minorities and people
of other religions,

00:38:10.390 --> 00:38:12.376
they started to
come into the store,

00:38:12.376 --> 00:38:14.204
and they started to poke at me.

00:38:14.204 --> 00:38:15.620
The knew I was
selling this music,

00:38:15.620 --> 00:38:18.436
and they started to
ask questions about it.

00:38:18.436 --> 00:38:20.840
And because we were
bonding over music,

00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:22.920
I started to become
friends with these people

00:38:22.920 --> 00:38:25.267
for the first time.

00:38:25.267 --> 00:38:27.475
And I started to understand
through our conversations

00:38:27.475 --> 00:38:29.609
was that the one thing
that we had in common

00:38:29.609 --> 00:38:33.710
was that I felt the same pain
as the Jewish person did, that I

00:38:33.710 --> 00:38:36.910
loved my wife and
my kids the same way

00:38:36.910 --> 00:38:40.230
that the same sex
couple loved each other.

00:38:40.230 --> 00:38:43.300
And I couldn't justify what
I was believing anymore.

00:38:43.300 --> 00:38:47.544
I couldn't reconcile my hate
with this new-found love

00:38:47.544 --> 00:38:49.210
and empathy that I
was starting to feel.

00:38:49.210 --> 00:38:53.740
It wasn't until I had
started to humanize people

00:38:53.740 --> 00:38:57.720
with empathy that it
started to break my shell.

00:38:57.720 --> 00:39:01.799
So I think that empathy is
something that's lacking.

00:39:01.799 --> 00:39:03.590
We were just in New
York this past weekend.

00:39:03.590 --> 00:39:07.470
And we went to the 9/11
Memorial, which is incredible.

00:39:07.470 --> 00:39:10.270
And it dawned on me that
the last time out country

00:39:10.270 --> 00:39:13.095
was really united, and
that all races got along

00:39:13.095 --> 00:39:15.560
with each other,
and all religions--

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:18.712
it didn't matter what religion
you were on September 11th.

00:39:18.712 --> 00:39:21.614
And it's a real
tragedy to me to think

00:39:21.614 --> 00:39:23.530
that the only time that
we can love each other

00:39:23.530 --> 00:39:27.750
is when something
tragic happens.

00:39:27.750 --> 00:39:29.370
And we had empathy
for each other.

00:39:29.370 --> 00:39:31.536
And we put ourselves
in each other's shoes.

00:39:31.536 --> 00:39:33.661
And we felt each other's
pain, and we came together

00:39:33.661 --> 00:39:34.464
as a country.

00:39:34.464 --> 00:39:38.368
And I think that that
empathy, if we can find a way

00:39:38.368 --> 00:39:40.076
to get that back
in our daily lives,

00:39:40.076 --> 00:39:42.130
without the tragedy
happening, we

00:39:42.130 --> 00:39:44.190
can finally begin to
understand and not

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:47.570
be afraid of people that
are different than us,

00:39:47.570 --> 00:39:51.394
and find a way to come together,
and hopefully make life better

00:39:51.394 --> 00:39:53.784
for everybody.

00:39:53.784 --> 00:39:55.696
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
I'm all [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:55.696 --> 00:39:58.995
Does anyone have any questions?

00:39:58.995 --> 00:39:59.870
Please go to the mic.

00:39:59.870 --> 00:40:01.245
We're doing some
recording today.

00:40:03.425 --> 00:40:03.925
Thank you.

00:40:03.925 --> 00:40:05.925
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: And
all the hands go down.

