AUDIENCE: So how--

00:40:09.477 --> 00:40:10.685
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: Is it on?

00:40:10.685 --> 00:40:11.185
It's not on.

00:40:14.645 --> 00:40:18.110
AUDIENCE: I don't know
how to turn it on.

00:40:18.110 --> 00:40:21.080
That button right there?

00:40:21.080 --> 00:40:22.610
That button right there.

00:40:22.610 --> 00:40:29.060
So how easy was it for
you to leave the movement?

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:33.150
It doesn't feel like it's
a membership you just

00:40:33.150 --> 00:40:35.560
stop paying on, right?

00:40:35.560 --> 00:40:39.950
It couldn't have been just one
day I'm out and I walk away.

00:40:39.950 --> 00:40:42.745
Can you talk a little bit
about what that experience was?

00:40:42.745 --> 00:40:44.120
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Absolutely.

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:45.644
And it's something
that I've shared

00:40:45.644 --> 00:40:47.620
with other people who've left.

00:40:47.620 --> 00:40:51.620
It's not an easy
process to leave.

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:54.120
One thing, throughout my
seven years of being involved,

00:40:54.120 --> 00:40:57.656
I always had these moments
of clarity, I call them.

00:40:57.656 --> 00:40:59.648
And they always happened
at really bad times

00:40:59.648 --> 00:41:01.640
when I was involved in a fight.

00:41:01.640 --> 00:41:04.130
And I would see somebody's
eyes open up the moment

00:41:04.130 --> 00:41:06.085
before they passed out.

00:41:06.085 --> 00:41:08.560
And it connected me to
them for just a moment.

00:41:08.560 --> 00:41:10.780
And then I would squash it away.

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:13.760
But for seven years, I always
had these moments of clarity.

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:16.734
And I credit my life before
that, my parents and my family

00:41:16.734 --> 00:41:18.622
not raising me that way.

00:41:18.622 --> 00:41:22.170
But it was a really
hard process to leave.

00:41:22.170 --> 00:41:23.200
And here's why.

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:25.640
So for seven years, I'd built
my whole social structure

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:28.660
within this movement.

00:41:28.660 --> 00:41:31.252
All my friends were people
who were in the movement.

00:41:31.252 --> 00:41:32.710
I didn't associate
with anybody who

00:41:32.710 --> 00:41:34.160
wasn't a part of the movement.

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:37.305
So when I decided to leave, I
pulled the white power music

00:41:37.305 --> 00:41:38.180
from my record store.

00:41:38.180 --> 00:41:42.160
And because it was 75% of my
sales, the business tanked.

00:41:42.160 --> 00:41:44.780
So I lost my job and
I closed the store.

00:41:44.780 --> 00:41:47.100
My wife at the time
and my children,

00:41:47.100 --> 00:41:49.890
who were just three and one,
left me because I was a part

00:41:49.890 --> 00:41:51.470
of the movement
and they weren't.

00:41:51.470 --> 00:41:53.595
I had always kind of been
that buffer between them.

00:41:53.595 --> 00:41:56.310
I had alienated myself from
my parents and my family,

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:58.580
so I didn't really have
a relationship with them.

00:41:58.580 --> 00:42:00.610
And I lost my whole
social structure.

00:42:00.610 --> 00:42:02.935
Every friend that I
had during every one

00:42:02.935 --> 00:42:06.220
of my formative
years, from 14 to 22,

00:42:06.220 --> 00:42:08.320
was a part of this movement.

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:11.190
So I think it was
hard because I was

00:42:11.190 --> 00:42:14.420
faced with losing everything.

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:17.184
It wasn't one thing
that got me out.

00:42:17.184 --> 00:42:18.275
It was series of events.

00:42:18.275 --> 00:42:22.220
It was my kids being
born, and their innocence,

00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:24.521
and me not being able
reconcile my life with the love

00:42:24.521 --> 00:42:25.354
that I had for them.

00:42:28.730 --> 00:42:32.790
But it took me awhile to
pull the trigger and leave.

00:42:32.790 --> 00:42:35.752
And closing the store,
getting divorced,

00:42:35.752 --> 00:42:38.850
retreating into my
depression all helped me.

00:42:38.850 --> 00:42:41.860
I was a leader of this group,
but I was selfish leader,

00:42:41.860 --> 00:42:44.449
meaning that I didn't really
have an heir-apparent that I

00:42:44.449 --> 00:42:45.980
had been grooming.

00:42:45.980 --> 00:42:49.448
So when I left, when I
decided I'm out, I'm done,

00:42:49.448 --> 00:42:52.352
the group kind of
imploded, luckily for me.

00:42:52.352 --> 00:42:54.397
Because had it not
imploded, I don't know

00:42:54.397 --> 00:42:57.100
that I'd be here right now.

00:42:57.100 --> 00:43:02.734
So it's a tough process, but
I was surrounded by love,

00:43:02.734 --> 00:43:03.900
even after, from my parents.

00:43:03.900 --> 00:43:05.319
That helped me out.

00:43:05.319 --> 00:43:07.684
That was major.

00:43:07.684 --> 00:43:09.207
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks
for being here.

00:43:09.207 --> 00:43:10.540
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: Thank you.

00:43:10.540 --> 00:43:13.880
AUDIENCE: So we can you
talk a little bit about what

00:43:13.880 --> 00:43:16.550
this movement did to your
relationship with your family

00:43:16.550 --> 00:43:20.180
as you went through it,
and then how it has changed

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:22.825
or how you think about
it with your relationship

00:43:22.825 --> 00:43:24.476
now with your kids and Britton?

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:30.090
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: My
relationship with my parents

00:43:30.090 --> 00:43:33.120
was really strained, obviously,
for those seven years.

00:43:33.120 --> 00:43:37.348
Because they spent every moment
trying to get me out, bail me

00:43:37.348 --> 00:43:39.555
out of jail, talk
me out of whatever

00:43:39.555 --> 00:43:41.430
I was going to do that
day that maybe was not

00:43:41.430 --> 00:43:44.390
going to be good for me.

00:43:44.390 --> 00:43:48.480
So it put a lot of
pressure on them.

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:51.943
But it also helped me have
a really great relationship

00:43:51.943 --> 00:43:53.148
with them now.

00:43:53.148 --> 00:43:57.490
They're still annoying
parents but in a good way.

00:43:57.490 --> 00:44:01.210
So I was able to rebuild
that relationship with them.

00:44:01.210 --> 00:44:02.700
My kids saved my life.

00:44:02.700 --> 00:44:06.412
If it hadn't been for my kids
being born when they did,

00:44:06.412 --> 00:44:09.710
when I was 19 to 21 I don't
know that I would have changed.

00:44:09.710 --> 00:44:12.926
Or it may have
taken a lot longer.

00:44:12.926 --> 00:44:15.190
And as matter of fact, my
kids were the first people

00:44:15.190 --> 00:44:20.156
to read my book when I finished
my first draft seven years ago.

00:44:20.156 --> 00:44:22.560
And it was important for
me to share it with them.

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:24.880
I had talked to them about
what I'd been through,

00:44:24.880 --> 00:44:28.420
but it was important for me
to get their feedback on it

00:44:28.420 --> 00:44:30.261
because I wanted them
to see who I had been

00:44:30.261 --> 00:44:33.950
and how I'd changed in
a more positive way.

00:44:33.950 --> 00:44:38.390
I'm also really lucky,
knock on fake wood,

00:44:38.390 --> 00:44:44.072
that my kids are nowhere
near as bad as I was.

00:44:44.072 --> 00:44:46.320
They're really good kids.

00:44:46.320 --> 00:44:48.630
When I'd met Britton, we'd
both been working for IBM

00:44:48.630 --> 00:44:50.210
at the time.

00:44:50.210 --> 00:44:52.980
I think it was 2001?

00:44:52.980 --> 00:44:53.480
Maybe?

00:44:55.835 --> 00:44:57.210
And she'd been
working in Dallas.

00:44:57.210 --> 00:44:59.000
I was here in Chicago,
and I was part

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:02.079
of a team that was feeding
sales opportunities

00:45:02.079 --> 00:45:04.120
to the inside sales team,
and Britton was working

00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:06.520
for inside sales at IBM.

00:45:06.520 --> 00:45:10.480
And we'd started
dating long distance.

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:12.723
And the first thing
that she did--

00:45:12.723 --> 00:45:14.347
and I don't want to
say she googled it,

00:45:14.347 --> 00:45:16.430
because I don't even think
that Google was around.

00:45:16.430 --> 00:45:17.440
She Altavistaed it.

00:45:17.440 --> 00:45:18.274
She found me online.

00:45:18.274 --> 00:45:19.856
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
Google was around.

00:45:19.856 --> 00:45:21.660
I'm pretty sure it was Google.

00:45:21.660 --> 00:45:22.710
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Were you using Google?

00:45:22.710 --> 00:45:23.710
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: Yeah.

00:45:23.710 --> 00:45:24.690
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
She googled my name

00:45:24.690 --> 00:45:26.290
and found something
that I'd written

00:45:26.290 --> 00:45:28.170
that had shown up online.

00:45:28.170 --> 00:45:31.370
And before we started
getting serious,

00:45:31.370 --> 00:45:32.760
she confronted me with it.

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:34.928
And I'm glad she did
because that was really

00:45:34.928 --> 00:45:36.792
one of the first
opportunities that I

00:45:36.792 --> 00:45:39.870
had to talk publicly to
another person about what

00:45:39.870 --> 00:45:41.670
I'd been through.

00:45:41.670 --> 00:45:44.124
And it started this
ball rolling of me

00:45:44.124 --> 00:45:45.597
talking more publicly about it.

00:45:47.394 --> 00:45:48.810
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
I didn't think

00:45:48.810 --> 00:45:50.830
it was as serious as it was.

00:45:50.830 --> 00:45:53.180
When I found it, it
was just a little piece

00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:55.873
on a bulletin board.

00:45:55.873 --> 00:45:58.754
And it sounded kind of militant,
but I was just like, oh,

00:45:58.754 --> 00:45:59.254
whatever.

00:45:59.254 --> 00:46:01.452
I was so white bread.

00:46:01.452 --> 00:46:03.118
And so I just instant
messaged him like,

00:46:03.118 --> 00:46:04.909
hey, are you as militant
as you used to be?

00:46:07.720 --> 00:46:09.230
And just very flippant.

00:46:09.230 --> 00:46:12.750
And he said, why?

00:46:12.750 --> 00:46:15.450
And I said, oh, I just
saw this thing online.

00:46:15.450 --> 00:46:17.800
And he's like, what?

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:20.490
And wanted me to
send him the link.

00:46:20.490 --> 00:46:23.770
I think Christian was
incredibly fortunate

00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:26.110
that he was involved
in the movement

00:46:26.110 --> 00:46:28.380
before the digital age.

00:46:28.380 --> 00:46:33.350
Because there really isn't
a digital record of what

00:46:33.350 --> 00:46:35.820
was going on at that time.

00:46:35.820 --> 00:46:37.695
Today would be insane.

00:46:37.695 --> 00:46:40.070
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: It's a
lot less forgiving, I think,

00:46:40.070 --> 00:46:40.470
with that record.

00:46:40.470 --> 00:46:42.000
So the thing that
she had found online

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:44.005
was something I'd written years
before that had been archived

00:46:44.005 --> 00:46:45.380
and somebody had put it online.

00:46:45.380 --> 00:46:48.786
And I had been out of the
movement for seven years

00:46:48.786 --> 00:46:51.287
already at that point
when she found it.

00:46:51.287 --> 00:46:52.870
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
And I grilled him.

00:46:52.870 --> 00:46:54.578
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
But she grilled me.

00:46:54.578 --> 00:46:57.870
And I'm glad she did, because it
started the ball rolling on me

00:46:57.870 --> 00:47:00.670
talking about it publicly.

00:47:00.670 --> 00:47:03.574
And then we met and here we are.

00:47:03.574 --> 00:47:05.026
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: Yes.

00:47:05.026 --> 00:47:09.527
I got a husband and a job
out of the whole deal.

00:47:09.527 --> 00:47:11.610
AUDIENCE: Hi, I also want
to say thanks for coming

00:47:11.610 --> 00:47:13.145
and thanks for making
your story public.

00:47:13.145 --> 00:47:15.228
I think it's really important
to get it out there.

00:47:15.228 --> 00:47:15.930
I was wondering.

00:47:15.930 --> 00:47:18.844
I forgot what the name of the
leader, the one who pulled up

00:47:18.844 --> 00:47:20.885
in the car in the alley,
what his name was, but i

00:47:20.885 --> 00:47:22.570
was wondering what
his trajectory was.

00:47:22.570 --> 00:47:25.748
And post-movement, did you ever
cross paths with him again?

00:47:25.748 --> 00:47:26.960
What happened to him?

00:47:26.960 --> 00:47:29.160
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
So what allowed

00:47:29.160 --> 00:47:31.880
me to step into a leadership
role when I was 16 years ago

00:47:31.880 --> 00:47:35.650
was that this
individual had gone

00:47:35.650 --> 00:47:39.271
to prison for some violence that
he had committed in Chicago.

00:47:42.428 --> 00:47:45.659
And he and a bunch of the
skinheads, they were all older,

00:47:45.659 --> 00:47:47.034
and had gotten
into some trouble,

00:47:47.034 --> 00:47:47.992
and had gone to prison.

00:47:47.992 --> 00:47:51.480
And I was suddenly left
with this void where

00:47:51.480 --> 00:47:54.430
I was one of the only people
left, me and the younger kids

00:47:54.430 --> 00:47:55.730
who I had recruited.

00:47:55.730 --> 00:47:59.450
So they had started to
look at me as the leader.

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:04.430
Clark had gone to
prison for seven years,

00:48:04.430 --> 00:48:06.870
had some mental issues.

00:48:06.870 --> 00:48:09.040
He and I had been
writing to each other,

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:10.728
and I recognized
pretty quickly that he

00:48:10.728 --> 00:48:12.560
had some mental problems.

00:48:12.560 --> 00:48:16.235
He's a brilliant guy, kind of
along the lines of a Charles

00:48:16.235 --> 00:48:19.800
Manson-- very
charismatic, super smart

00:48:19.800 --> 00:48:22.160
but in a very twisted way.

00:48:22.160 --> 00:48:27.762
And I saw him one more time
in 1996 or '97 after he'd

00:48:27.762 --> 00:48:28.990
gotten out of prison.

00:48:28.990 --> 00:48:31.085
He had shown up
at one of the punk

00:48:31.085 --> 00:48:33.168
rock shows that I had with
this non-political band

00:48:33.168 --> 00:48:34.906
that I was playing in.

00:48:34.906 --> 00:48:37.430
And I haven't seen him since.

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:38.850
I don't know where he is.

00:48:38.850 --> 00:48:39.600
I've heard rumors.

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:41.240
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
Not for lack of tyring.

00:48:41.240 --> 00:48:41.980
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Yeah, I've tried.

00:48:41.980 --> 00:48:43.940
I mean, researching,
fact checking just

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:46.334
for myself and my book.

00:48:46.334 --> 00:48:47.250
I can't find anything.

00:48:47.250 --> 00:48:51.295
I mean, part of it is because
he existed before the internet.

00:48:51.295 --> 00:48:52.420
But I can't-- I don't know.

00:48:52.420 --> 00:48:53.461
I think he's still alive.

00:48:53.461 --> 00:48:55.070
I think he's still in Chicago.

00:48:55.070 --> 00:48:59.067
I hope he's not damaging
anybody anymore.

00:48:59.067 --> 00:49:02.049
I suspect he is,
but I don't know.

00:49:02.049 --> 00:49:03.043
Yes?

00:49:03.043 --> 00:49:06.490
AUDIENCE: Hi, I have
two questions, actually.

00:49:06.490 --> 00:49:09.910
Number one, I'm just
curious if you're

00:49:09.910 --> 00:49:12.360
familiar with the film
"American History X"

00:49:12.360 --> 00:49:15.880
and if you had any perspective
on how realistic that was.

00:49:15.880 --> 00:49:17.620
Obviously, it was
Hollywood, but I just

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.150
would love to get your
perspective on it.

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:22.979
Number two, just a
personal question,

00:49:22.979 --> 00:49:25.270
how would I recognize one of
these people on the street

00:49:25.270 --> 00:49:26.353
if they're not a skinhead?

00:49:26.353 --> 00:49:27.230
Just curious.

00:49:27.230 --> 00:49:29.105
Also what neighborhoods
they may hang out in.

00:49:31.280 --> 00:49:33.890
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: I'll
start with your second question.

00:49:33.890 --> 00:49:37.040
I don't know how you
will recognize them

00:49:37.040 --> 00:49:39.130
because they do a really
good job of blending in.

00:49:39.130 --> 00:49:42.700
A lot of folks went to
more mainstream, far

00:49:42.700 --> 00:49:45.202
right organizations
like the Tea Party.

00:49:45.202 --> 00:49:46.618
Not that all tea
partiers are bad,

00:49:46.618 --> 00:49:47.980
if there's anybody in the room.

00:49:47.980 --> 00:49:51.820
But it's hard.

00:49:51.820 --> 00:49:53.195
It's really hard
spot them, which

00:49:53.195 --> 00:49:55.153
is why we do a lot of
work with law enforcement

00:49:55.153 --> 00:49:57.518
to help them understand the
mindset and the buzzwords

00:49:57.518 --> 00:50:00.410
that they use.

00:50:00.410 --> 00:50:05.820
I think it's a lot less active
in Chicago than it used to be,

00:50:05.820 --> 00:50:08.575
but I don't know that for sure.

00:50:08.575 --> 00:50:10.200
Your first question,
what was the film?

00:50:10.200 --> 00:50:11.160
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
"American History X."

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:12.910
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
"American History X,

00:50:12.910 --> 00:50:16.522
so "American History X" was
based on several people.

00:50:16.522 --> 00:50:17.980
It's a composite
of several people.

00:50:20.780 --> 00:50:23.460
I tend to believe
that it's partly

00:50:23.460 --> 00:50:26.920
based on me and some
folks that I know.

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:29.274
Though I can't confirm that,
when you read the book,

00:50:29.274 --> 00:50:31.315
you'll find that there
are a lot of similarities.

00:50:33.691 --> 00:50:35.774
BRITTON PICCIOLINI:
[INAUDIBLE] in Life After Hate

00:50:35.774 --> 00:50:38.700
with you is another person.

00:50:38.700 --> 00:50:40.888
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: Yeah,
some people that I know,

00:50:40.888 --> 00:50:42.262
it could have been
based on them.

00:50:42.262 --> 00:50:44.510
I don't know.

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:47.712
As to how realistic it is,
it was pretty realistic.

00:50:47.712 --> 00:50:50.580
I'd have to say that, for
a Hollywood production,

00:50:50.580 --> 00:50:52.500
it was pretty accurate.

00:50:52.500 --> 00:50:54.820
There's a lot of violence.

00:50:54.820 --> 00:50:57.150
Music plays a central part
like it did in the movie.

00:50:57.150 --> 00:51:00.233
There's always that
charismatic older person

00:51:00.233 --> 00:51:04.560
who is recruiting and
holding these meetings.

00:51:04.560 --> 00:51:07.206
They're messed up people
that drink a lot, and do

00:51:07.206 --> 00:51:09.477
a lot of drugs, and cause a
lot of violence, sometimes

00:51:09.477 --> 00:51:10.060
to each other.

00:51:15.774 --> 00:51:17.690
AUDIENCE: Sorry, can I
ask one other question?

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:18.020
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Absolutely.

00:51:18.020 --> 00:51:19.700
AUDIENCE: Could you
tell us, Christian,

00:51:19.700 --> 00:51:23.660
what is a day in a
life of a skinhead.

00:51:23.660 --> 00:51:25.530
What does it look like?

00:51:25.530 --> 00:51:26.892
What are they thinking?

00:51:26.892 --> 00:51:27.725
What are they doing?

00:51:31.250 --> 00:51:35.020
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
For me, you wake up,

00:51:35.020 --> 00:51:39.930
you're probably unemployed or
working a pretty menial job.

00:51:39.930 --> 00:51:45.840
There is a working class
ethic, although they rarely

00:51:45.840 --> 00:51:46.960
stick to it.

00:51:46.960 --> 00:51:49.680
They kind of pride themselves
on this middle class,

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:52.088
working class ethic.

00:51:52.088 --> 00:51:55.440
But they drink a lot.

00:51:55.440 --> 00:51:59.834
They do drugs, even
though they proclaim

00:51:59.834 --> 00:52:01.500
that they don't because
they're supposed

00:52:01.500 --> 00:52:05.393
to be these supreme beings.

00:52:05.393 --> 00:52:06.970
But it's a lot of violence.

00:52:06.970 --> 00:52:09.659
I mean, you're constantly
fighting with somebody

00:52:09.659 --> 00:52:10.575
or watching your back.

00:52:10.575 --> 00:52:13.807
Because all you do is you're
trying to recruit people.

00:52:13.807 --> 00:52:14.890
You're preaching violence.

00:52:14.890 --> 00:52:16.180
And they spin it.

00:52:16.180 --> 00:52:18.890
So one thing that skinheads
are really good at,

00:52:18.890 --> 00:52:21.480
or just racists in
general, is they

00:52:21.480 --> 00:52:23.070
say it's about white pride.

00:52:23.070 --> 00:52:24.445
We're just proud of who we are.

00:52:24.445 --> 00:52:26.380
And when people
attack who we are,

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:27.672
that's when we get violent.

00:52:27.672 --> 00:52:29.560
Well, it's bullshit.

00:52:29.560 --> 00:52:31.310
Because behind the
scenes and internally,

00:52:31.310 --> 00:52:32.710
it really is about supremacy.

00:52:32.710 --> 00:52:33.695
It is about power.

00:52:33.695 --> 00:52:39.320
It really is about
marginalizing and alienating

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:41.240
other people that
aren't like you.

00:52:41.240 --> 00:52:43.390
So while they have
this outward marketing

00:52:43.390 --> 00:52:47.655
face where it's all European
heritage, and pride, and--

00:52:47.655 --> 00:52:48.780
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: Purity.

00:52:48.780 --> 00:52:50.250
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: It's not.

00:52:50.250 --> 00:52:55.506
It really is about violence,
about hate, and prejudice.

00:52:55.506 --> 00:52:58.290
And it's a pretty bad lifestyle.

00:52:58.290 --> 00:53:00.750
BRITTON PICCIOLINI: What I
found the most interesting

00:53:00.750 --> 00:53:05.300
is that it was just a lot of
marketing genius at the time.

00:53:05.300 --> 00:53:08.033
There was just tons
and tons of promotion.

00:53:13.830 --> 00:53:16.176
AUDIENCE: I just also
wanted to say thank you

00:53:16.176 --> 00:53:17.802
for bringing out the story.

00:53:17.802 --> 00:53:20.350
I think it's important
for other kids who might

00:53:20.350 --> 00:53:21.520
consider this as an option.

00:53:21.520 --> 00:53:22.978
They know there's
a story out there

00:53:22.978 --> 00:53:25.311
that's a counter-story, a
counter-narrative to what they

00:53:25.311 --> 00:53:26.920
hear.

00:53:26.920 --> 00:53:29.933
I mean, it makes my
heart race hearing all

00:53:29.933 --> 00:53:32.460
of this-- just confrontations.

00:53:32.460 --> 00:53:36.352
And when this topic comes
up, its just so dangerous.

00:53:36.352 --> 00:53:37.727
And you're always
thinking you've

00:53:37.727 --> 00:53:39.356
got to watch your back
or somebody's going

00:53:39.356 --> 00:53:40.272
to confront something.

00:53:40.272 --> 00:53:42.675
Even here sitting here talking
with someone as friendly

00:53:42.675 --> 00:53:44.200
as you.

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:45.727
So I can only
imagine how much it

00:53:45.727 --> 00:53:48.940
is for you to have to face
all this and this history.

00:53:48.940 --> 00:53:50.770
So thank you very
much for sharing that.

00:53:50.770 --> 00:53:53.500
I guess my question makes sense.

00:53:53.500 --> 00:53:57.026
Something that you said
about taking responsibility

00:53:57.026 --> 00:54:01.820
or scapegoating, even
just last week there's

00:54:01.820 --> 00:54:05.946
somebody or some group posting
signs along the Lake Shore bike

00:54:05.946 --> 00:54:08.340
trail with caricatures
of homeless people

00:54:08.340 --> 00:54:11.585
and usual with
blackface kind of stuff.

00:54:11.585 --> 00:54:13.879
Etcetera, right?

00:54:13.879 --> 00:54:15.420
But the message
they're sending isn't

00:54:15.420 --> 00:54:18.120
too different than from
what we tend to hear just

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:22.170
in normal mainstream talk-- just
stereotypes where we scapegoat.

00:54:22.170 --> 00:54:24.391
Homeless people don't
want to get a job,

00:54:24.391 --> 00:54:28.320
or women don't want to do
something smart and scientific,

00:54:28.320 --> 00:54:29.196
or whatever?

00:54:29.196 --> 00:54:31.390
Jews are controlling the
media and everything else

00:54:31.390 --> 00:54:33.900
like you said.

00:54:33.900 --> 00:54:35.430
Or Latinos are just gangbangers.

00:54:35.430 --> 00:54:38.380
So I just wonder how
much the stereotypes that

00:54:38.380 --> 00:54:42.750
permeate in mainstream
society envelope or provide

00:54:42.750 --> 00:54:47.363
cover for what you said the
skinheads do, which is blend in

00:54:47.363 --> 00:54:49.210
and operate that way.

00:54:49.210 --> 00:54:51.030
AUDIENCE: Yeah, any
time that would happen,

00:54:51.030 --> 00:54:55.144
that was a spark where
we threw gasoline on it.

00:54:55.144 --> 00:54:56.310
And that's how we recruited.

00:54:56.310 --> 00:54:59.574
So anytime we would hear
somebody say something pretty

00:54:59.574 --> 00:55:01.740
normal, like what you're
talking about-- not normal,

00:55:01.740 --> 00:55:05.705
but that's pervasive in society
today-- we would cozy up

00:55:05.705 --> 00:55:06.705
to them and say, ah-hah.

00:55:06.705 --> 00:55:07.980
Yes, you're right.

00:55:07.980 --> 00:55:10.420
And start to put the
gasoline on that fire

00:55:10.420 --> 00:55:13.505
and eventually recruit
them in over time.

00:55:13.505 --> 00:55:16.280
And unfortunately,
those stereotypes

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:21.154
are flourishing in the
movement and in society.

00:55:21.154 --> 00:55:24.410
And as we all know, most
times it's not true.

00:55:24.410 --> 00:55:29.140
So we got to be very,
very good at using

00:55:29.140 --> 00:55:31.055
those stereotypes
to recruit people

00:55:31.055 --> 00:55:32.096
and pull them in further.

00:55:34.910 --> 00:55:37.183
And all we can do
is be ourselves

00:55:37.183 --> 00:55:39.057
and prove that those
stereotypes don't exist.

00:55:42.410 --> 00:55:45.284
AUDIENCE: Hi, is this on?

00:55:45.284 --> 00:55:47.690
I always want to say
thank you for coming.

00:55:47.690 --> 00:55:51.140
It's such an engrossing story.

00:55:51.140 --> 00:55:56.990
I'm from New York, and I've seen
a lot of local politics going

00:55:56.990 --> 00:55:57.975
very right wing.

00:55:57.975 --> 00:55:59.520
And it's very frightening.

00:55:59.520 --> 00:56:04.080
And they ride on a ticket
of nationalism, immigration,

00:56:04.080 --> 00:56:07.960
jobs-- that kind of thing.

00:56:07.960 --> 00:56:13.138
So do you see that
populist movement, A,

00:56:13.138 --> 00:56:14.096
growing-- I don't know.

00:56:14.096 --> 00:56:16.269
I'm not too familiar
with American politics--

00:56:16.269 --> 00:56:20.181
on a local level,
but also do you see

00:56:20.181 --> 00:56:23.239
the membership of these
skinhead gangs growing?

00:56:23.239 --> 00:56:24.530
Or is this declining right now?

00:56:24.530 --> 00:56:25.739
What do you think?

00:56:25.739 --> 00:56:27.280
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
Well, I can you

00:56:27.280 --> 00:56:31.863
tell that when President
Obama was elected that law

00:56:31.863 --> 00:56:33.321
enforcement and
groups like the ADL

00:56:33.321 --> 00:56:36.092
and the Southern Poverty Law
Center saw massive spikes

00:56:36.092 --> 00:56:37.300
in enrollment in hate groups.

00:56:41.159 --> 00:56:42.450
I do think it's happening here.

00:56:42.450 --> 00:56:47.020
I think that our politics are
such that it's always divided.

00:56:47.020 --> 00:56:50.480
There's always two opposing
sides to everything

00:56:50.480 --> 00:56:53.420
and never a whole lot of
meeting in the middle.

00:56:53.420 --> 00:56:55.120
And I have experienced
what you're

00:56:55.120 --> 00:56:57.510
talking about in
Europe where they

00:56:57.510 --> 00:57:00.910
play on nationalist tendencies.

00:57:00.910 --> 00:57:04.446
And it works, unfortunately.

00:57:04.446 --> 00:57:06.070
And I think it's
starting to work here.

00:57:06.070 --> 00:57:10.530
I think we're seeing
a lot of homegrown,

00:57:10.530 --> 00:57:13.690
far right nationalist
movements, Sovereign Citizen

00:57:13.690 --> 00:57:20.886
groups, militia groups,
extreme constitutionalists.

00:57:20.886 --> 00:57:24.830
They're doing some of the
same things in this country.

00:57:24.830 --> 00:57:27.295
And the environment
is ripe for that now.

00:57:27.295 --> 00:57:29.267
At least it has been
over the last decade

00:57:29.267 --> 00:57:32.321
where unemployment
maybe has been higher.

00:57:32.321 --> 00:57:35.325
And certainly when
there's an instance

00:57:35.325 --> 00:57:38.300
of any kind of
foreign terrorism,

00:57:38.300 --> 00:57:39.980
you can bet that
far right groups

00:57:39.980 --> 00:57:42.020
are going to jump
on that and use

00:57:42.020 --> 00:57:43.756
that to incite other people.

00:57:47.730 --> 00:57:51.590
AUDIENCE: Here in our country,
I feel like a lot of our laws

00:57:51.590 --> 00:57:53.500
protect white
supremacy in regards

00:57:53.500 --> 00:57:56.820
to assembly and
free speech, whereas

00:57:56.820 --> 00:57:59.265
in our European
counterparts, a lot of that

00:57:59.265 --> 00:58:04.670
is actually illegal to assemble
or to have hate speech.

00:58:04.670 --> 00:58:08.710
What are your thoughts on how
our country protects, loosely,

00:58:08.710 --> 00:58:10.040
the ability to do that?

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:11.920
And do you think laws
should be changed?

00:58:16.620 --> 00:58:19.830
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: I
believe in free speech.

00:58:19.830 --> 00:58:25.300
And I think while our country
may protect hate speech

00:58:25.300 --> 00:58:28.490
and assembly by hate
groups, in theory,

00:58:28.490 --> 00:58:30.717
it also protects
everybody else and allows

00:58:30.717 --> 00:58:32.640
them to have those freedoms.

00:58:32.640 --> 00:58:34.080
I know in countries
like Germany,

00:58:34.080 --> 00:58:39.165
the use of the swastika or
even saluting is illegal.

00:58:39.165 --> 00:58:40.534
You can go to jail for that.

00:58:43.190 --> 00:58:47.658
I don't know that the government
or law enforcement making

00:58:47.658 --> 00:58:49.610
rules for us not to
say things or do things

00:58:49.610 --> 00:58:51.074
is the right answer.

00:58:51.074 --> 00:58:53.838
I think we as people just need
to do a better job of treating

00:58:53.838 --> 00:58:55.870
other people with respect
and as human beings

00:58:55.870 --> 00:58:58.680
to eliminate that
problem and still keep

00:58:58.680 --> 00:59:01.380
the freedoms that we have.

00:59:01.380 --> 00:59:03.370
That's a tough question.

00:59:03.370 --> 00:59:05.250
Would I love to silence them?

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:07.310
Absolutely.

00:59:07.310 --> 00:59:09.070
Do I think it's the
right thing to do?

